    'smith_machine_squat',
    'Smith machine squat',
    '{"merged_steps": ["Technique and Execution The Smith machine squat is a variation of the traditional barbell squat that uses a guided, fixed-path barbell.", "Here''s a detailed breakdown of the proper technique: Starting Position Foot Placement: Position feet slightly forward of the bar, about shoulder-width apart Bar Position: Rest the bar on your upper trapezius/shoulders, similar to a traditional back squat Stance: Feet can be slightly angled outward for natural hip rotation Squat Movement Unrack the bar by rotating it to release from the safety hooks Slowly lower your body by bending knees and hips Descend until thighs are parallel to the ground (or slightly below) Pause briefly at the bottom of the movement Drive through your heels to return to the starting position Benefits and Considerations Advantages Reduced Balance Requirements: Fixed bar path makes it easier for beginners Controlled Movement: Less risk of improper form compared to free weight squats Isolation: Allows focused leg muscle development"], "sources": [{"source": "wger", "file": "C:\\Users\\kaiqu\\Desktop\\SOMMA\\datasets\\wger-master\\wger\\exercises\\fixtures\\exercise-base-data.json", "steps": ["Technique and Execution The Smith machine squat is a variation of the traditional barbell squat that uses a guided, fixed-path barbell.", "Here''s a detailed breakdown of the proper technique: Starting Position Foot Placement: Position feet slightly forward of the bar, about shoulder-width apart Bar Position: Rest the bar on your upper trapezius/shoulders, similar to a traditional back squat Stance: Feet can be slightly angled outward for natural hip rotation Squat Movement Unrack the bar by rotating it to release from the safety hooks Slowly lower your body by bending knees and hips Descend until thighs are parallel to the ground (or slightly below) Pause briefly at the bottom of the movement Drive through your heels to return to the starting position Benefits and Considerations Advantages Reduced Balance Requirements: Fixed bar path makes it easier for beginners Controlled Movement: Less risk of improper form compared to free weight squats Isolation: Allows focused leg muscle development"], "description": "Technique and Execution The Smith machine squat is a variation of the traditional barbell squat that uses a guided, fixed-path barbell. Here''s a detailed breakdown of the proper technique: Starting Position Foot Placement: Position feet slightly forward of the bar, about shoulder-width apart Bar Position: Rest the bar on your upper trapezius/shoulders, similar to a traditional back squat Stance: Feet can be slightly angled outward for natural hip rotation Squat Movement Unrack the bar by rotating it to release from the safety hooks Slowly lower your body by bending knees and hips Descend until thighs are parallel to the ground (or slightly below) Pause briefly at the bottom of the movement Drive through your heels to return to the starting position Benefits and Considerations Advantages Reduced Balance Requirements: Fixed bar path makes it easier for beginners Controlled Movement: Less risk of improper form compared to free weight squats Isolation: Allows focused leg muscle development"}], "summary": "Technique and Execution The Smith machine squat is a variation of the traditional barbell squat that uses a guided, fixed-path barbell. Here''s a detailed breakdown of the proper technique: Starting Position Foot Placement: Position feet slightly forward of the bar, about shoulder-width apart Bar Position: Rest the bar on your upper trapezius/shoulders, similar to a traditional back squat Stance: Feet can be slightly angled outward for natural hip rotation Squat Movement Unrack the bar by rotating it to release from the safety hooks Slowly lower your body by bending knees and hips Descend until thighs are parallel to the ground (or slightly below) Pause briefly at the bottom of the movement Drive through your heels to return to the starting position Benefits and Considerations Advantages Reduced Balance Requirements: Fixed bar path makes it easier for beginners Controlled Movement: Less risk of improper form compared to free weight squats Isolation: Allows focused leg muscle development", "cues": "Technique and Execution The Smith machine squat is a variation of the traditional barbell squat that uses a guided, fixed-path barbell. Here''s a detailed breakdown of the proper technique: Starting Position Foot Placement: Position feet slightly forward of the bar, about shoulder-width apart Bar Position: Rest the bar on your upper trapezius/shoulders, similar to a traditional back squat Stance: Feet can be slightly angled outward for natural hip rotation Squat Movement Unrack the bar by rotating it to release from the safety hooks Slowly lower your body by bending knees and hips Descend until thighs are parallel to the ground (or slightly below) Pause briefly at the bottom of the movement Drive through your heels to return to the starting position Benefits and Considerations Advantages Reduced Balance Requirements: Fixed bar path makes it easier for beginners Controlled Movement: Less risk of improper form compared to free weight squats Isolation: Allows focused leg muscle development"}'::jsonb,
